section*
  code $loinc#67852-4 Hospital Admission evaluation note
  title Admission evaluation
  text """Ms. Zuzanna Lewandowska, a 45-year-old Polish female, presented to the emergency department while on vacation in France, approximately two hours after eating at a buffet. She reported acute nausea, abdominal cramping, and vomiting. The initial working diagnosis was suspected food poisoning.<p/>On admission, vital signs were stable. The patient appeared mildly dehydrated but was haemodynamically stable with no signs of anaphylaxis or airway involvement. Gastric lavage was performed and gastric contents were submitted for toxicological and microbiological analysis. Intravenous fluid therapy was commenced for rehydration and supportive care."""
section*
  type allergy
  code $loinc#48765-2 Allergies and adverse reactions Document
  title Allergies and Intolerances
  text """Ms. Lewandowska has a known allergy to peanuts, confirmed during detailed anamnesis on day 2 of admission. The allergy had not been initially disclosed. Accidental ingestion of peanut cream contained in a regional French pastry is identified as the cause of this admission."""
  entry*
    type allergy
    code $sct#256349002 Peanut (substance)
    criticality high
    status active
    reaction $sct#473460002 Allergic gastrointestinal disorder (disorder)
    severity moderate
section*
  type hospitalcourse
  code $loinc#8648-8 Hospital Course
  text = """Following admission, Ms. Lewandowska received intravenous fluid therapy for rehydration and supportive monitoring. Gastric content analysis and 24-hour observation yielded no evidence of bacterial or toxic foodborne illness, effectively ruling out food poisoning.<p/>A detailed anamnesis on the following day revealed that the patient had unknowingly consumed a local French pastry containing peanut cream. She confirmed a pre-existing peanut allergy during this interview. The clinical presentation was re-evaluated as an acute non-anaphylactic gastrointestinal allergic reaction to accidental peanut ingestion.<p/>The patient remained haemodynamically stable throughout her stay with no signs of anaphylaxis, urticaria, or respiratory involvement. Symptoms resolved progressively with supportive care. No pharmacological treatment was required beyond the initial hydration. The patient was discharged after 48 hours in good condition."""
